This paper is primarily focused on language modeling, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a new neural network architecture, which involves learning to interpolate between two states, and this falls under the category of machine learning (ML). Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses regularization techniques to improve the performance of the model, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for subword-level language modeling, which falls under the category of computer vision (CV), making cs.CV a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses recurrent neural networks (RNNs) for language modeling, which falls under the category of neural networks (NE), making cs.NE another possible sub-category.
